Unisim is currently in Equinor software portfolio and is prioritised for qualification. Unisim is widely used for oil industry process simulations and is not a specialist tool for CO2-applications. 

There are other alternatives out there that may turn out to be better on short term deliveries, but the aim is to help vendor improve Unisim where shortcomings are uncovered,. 

Unisim is set to be TRL2 for CCS applications because no verification against experimental data for relevant conditions have been made prior to this work. 

 

As described under "Purpose" in the Business Case, there is a need to verify or benchmark steady state process behaviour as well as unsteady-state/dynamic behaviour. The two being used to distinguish between TRL3 and TRL4 respectively. 

 

The scope of work for this TDP is to:

  • Gather experimental process data from ongoing industry projects where Equinor has access. 
  • Set up and run simulations for cases reported and literature
  • Benchmark performance iof UniSim against real data
  • Collaboration with suppliers on improving thermodynalic and flow models in Unisim 
  • Use benchmarking results to create overview of UniSim performance for different purposes and different operational windows. 

The tables below list which result packages are relevant for what type of unit operation (static or dynamic) and how the results will be used to benchmark the simulation tool. 

 

 

The deliverables from this TDP will be: 

  • Assessment relevant available process simulation tools (pre-study, completed 2020)
  • Benchmarked Unisim with available experimental data for static and dynamic conditions
  • Best Practise for prosess simulation of CO2. This can be in form of reports, data or learning material for simulation tools. Or it can be as input to GL0458 for CO2 safety in CCS 
  • Collaboration vith vendor of process simulation tool in order to improve performance. 
  • New data

technologyDetails.technologyName: Ultrasonic doppler measurements while drilling for identification and quantification of influx/efflux in boreholes
technologyDetails.purpose:
Inspired by ultrasound used in medicine
Ultrasonic wellbore imaging possible today, but could we also monitor fluid dynamics?
What if we could quantify in real time fluid gains or losses?

Wellbore stability, including fluid losses and/or wellbore influx during drilling is among the highest risk factors in the well construction process.
Early detection and counteraction is crucial to prevent escalation of wellbore problems
Ultrasonic Doppler While Drilling enables both early detection and a quantitative estimate of fluid losses and/or gains (influx/efflux area, geometry, velocity and direction)
Likewise, the effect of the mitigating actions initiated can be monitored
technologyDetails.description:
This project investigates the feasibility of further development of existing ultrasonic technologies commercially available during drilling operations, but advances from current static ultrasonic imaging to dynamic borehole imaging utilizing ultrasonic doppler measurements.

 


The technology would primarily include a logging while drilling "LWD" component (part of the bottom hole assembly "BHA"), consisting of one or several ultrasonic transponders placed close (typically within 10-30 m) to the drillbit, continuously measuring the wellbore fluids' velocity and flow direction, creating a fluid dynamics wellbore image during the drilling operation.

As ultrasonic doppler measurements are particularly sensitive to radial movements (movements towards/away from the transponder) it is believed that the axial fluid movements (the mud flow) are distinguishable from fluids moving from the formation into the wellbore (influx or gain) and wellbore fluid losses into the formation.

technologyDetails.purpose:
WHY - Objectives of Technology
Subsea operations need to become more efficient in time and costs, which leads to the automatization of the processes, and the standardization of the solution spanning exploration, monitoring and maintenance.
 
This demands the automatization of independent and autonomous underwater vehicles which can be easily modified to perform almost any subsea task available.
 
An example:
Reservoirs are getting smaller and hide in more complex geology. Finding and monitoring of reservoirs need increasingly precise and better geophysical data only available on the seabed. We need a more efficient system which collects better data with less impact. Standard towed streamer (TS) data is cheap but Ocean-Bottom Seismic (OBS) using Remotely-Operated Vehicles (ROV) or ropes are today at least 5 times more expensive. Link to video
A-OBS - WHY v2.png 
 
Business impact
A general platform which can be used for exploration, monitoring, seep/CO2 detection, seabed mining & sampling, hazard mapping, pipeline inspection, interventions, etc.
An open hardware standard for suppliers to build on
A digitalization drive to bring autonomy from your lawn mower to the deep sea
Fewer HSE events
Less human interaction
Less environmental impact
Reduced CO2
 
Example more efficiency: ca.9 times faster deployment nodes, faster recovery, less vessel time:
Survey cost reduced by at least half
Better data: better imaging of smaller targets due to more receivers, equal inline and crossline coverage, also for hazards
The SeaHorse A-OBS system enables Equinor to find and exploit more oil & gas resources
